    {
      "id": "0007ea7aefb0765949b5c0593800ba75b8d7bf70",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 136,
        "name": "Alexey Lyashkov",
        "email": "alexey.lyashkov@hpe.com",
        "username": "shadow"
      },
      "date": "2020-04-13 10:44:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI'm sorry, I was busy with data corruption issue covered all 2.0 lustre code.\n(see LU-13416).\n\nAs about Sebastien concern - it's completely wrong. rpm builds have an \"auto requirement\"  scripts who add an libselinux.so (or what is real library name) into requirements for package.\nSo library dependences completely don't needs and it's source of problems with building packages against of different rpm based distributions. (simple example SuSe don't have a selinux and use an apparmor).\n\nThese builds checked by 4 scripts (RHEL 7.6/8.1, SLES12/15) over ~10 configurations each. example of one of scripts is - https://pastebin.com/JdsrjxT7",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "017dbbbd186123d97e89379394fc8966a829b499",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 136,
        "name": "Alexey Lyashkov",
        "email": "alexey.lyashkov@hpe.com",
        "username": "shadow"
      },
      "date": "2020-04-13 17:14:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nfrom rpm to test build this change\n\n# rpm -qp -i -R lustre-client-2.13.52_185_ge628b7c_dirty-1.el7.x86_64.rpm  | grep selinux\nlibselinux\nlibselinux.so.1()(64bit)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "e3e68d8a9201b536f031455a03f6e36a959bef5f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 136,
        "name": "Alexey Lyashkov",
        "email": "alexey.lyashkov@hpe.com",
        "username": "shadow"
      },
      "date": "2020-04-13 17:18:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nlots more examples of auto scripts.\n rpm -qp -i -R lustre-client-2.13.52_185_ge628b7c_dirty-1.el7.x86_64.rpm  | grep perl\n/usr/bin/perl\nperl(File::Basename)\nperl(Getopt::Long)\nperl(Getopt::Std)\nperl(POSIX)\nperl(strict)\n\ndon't know about package names - but it know about modules need to be provided.\n# yum provides 'perl(File::Basename)'\n\n4:perl-5.16.3-294.el7_6.x86_64 : Practical Extraction and Report Language\nRepo        : base\nMatched from:\nProvides    : perl(File::Basename) = 2.84\n\n\n\n4:perl-5.16.3-294.el7_6.x86_64 : Practical Extraction and Report Language\nRepo        : @updates\nMatched from:\nProvides    : perl(File::Basename) = 2.84",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
